defaultFactual information of which we would like the com
defaultmittee to be aware 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe issue of women engineers and scientists goes 
defaultback to
default WW1 as seen in historical record of the Women’s Engineering Society (WES). Since the early years there have been almost annual enquiries into aspects of this issue for many years
default and ‘wake-up calls’ followed by short term projects every decade since the 1970s
default and even before
default. The progress has been modest, at best, and short term at worst. There is too much fragmentation of effort and re-invention of wheels. There is a need for act
defaultion rather than examining, over and over again, why the situation exists. In the meantime, expensively-educated women are ‘lost’ to STEM careers in droves, for reasons not of their choosing. 
default&#xa0;
defaultTable 1 lists some of the many projects undertaken to help prog
defaultress women in their chosen careers as a timeline. 
defaultNote that this list represents just the last 30 years and there were numerous schemes and projects from about 1970 onwards, and even many efforts both during and 
defaultbetween
default the two world wars.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default“There have 
defaultbeen many laudable schemes that have attempted to stem this loss of talent, but which, because of their often ad hoc, partial and short-term nature, have failed to have a sustained impact.”
default  [Tapping all our Talents: Women in science, technology, engineeri
defaultng and mathematics: a strategy for Scotland
default. RSE. 
default 2012]
